In "Decrypto", it is not the terms behind the secret foil that should be guessed, but its encryption keys.
His task in this case: He should describe - in this order and in this example - the terms "dice", "fixed" and "window" - in such a way that his own team recognizes the correct order and the opposing team as far as possible not; because that wins the game if he manages to crack the code twice.
So the encryptor notes and reads aloud: "toss" for the dice, "lots" as opposed to feast; here, of course, something like "Party" would be possible and "Prague" because he paid attention at school and knows the fall of the window there.
So it goes round by round, team by team.
You don't know the terms of the other side - but you can put them together better with every hint that the encryptor gives there.
The descriptions should be as mysterious as possible, but not too crazy, otherwise you make it unnecessarily difficult for your team.
Unfortunately, the most cryptic thing about "Decrypto" is the rule book.
The other players probably have to study it quite long and in detail until they can finally play.
The explanatory video under decrypto.info on the net makes it easier.
But once you get started, you will be fascinated by how much feeling there is in this inconspicuous game.
Overall, however, "Decrypto" is not quite as conclusive as its predecessor and genre leader "Codenames", which also puts an agent theme on a game of a few words, but is much better to play in small groups.
