Betriebswerk Pressig was home of the pusher locomotives
The locomotive depot in Pressig was the hub in the Franconian Forest for decades.
In 1991, a piece of railway history came to an end.
"When buffers banged on buffers, you could hear it all over the press," recalls Georg Dinkel, who archives the history of the town and the station.
That didn't upset anyone.
Then the brakes squealed and the wagons rattled.
That was pure railway.
Statements that symbolize Dinkel's homeland Pressig.
Nowhere else in the Franconian Forest was a place so shaped by the railway.
Here was the starting point of the steep ramp mountain route to the north, which after an ascent of about 220 meters in altitude has its apex in Steinbach am Wald.
In order to cope with this, train and pusher locomotives were needed in the past, which had their home in Pressig.
In 1901, the Bavarian state parliament approved the construction of a locomotive depot with 21 engine sheds, apprentice workshop, catenary and railway maintenance department.
"The centrepiece was the turntable, which had a diameter of 18 metres after a conversion in 1899," says Norbert Heidrich from Hirschaid, railway historian and professional railway worker for 47 years.
The Pressig locomotive depot, which was subordinated to Bamberg in 1968, also operated locomotives for the branch lines Pressig - Tettau, Ludwigsstadt - Lehesten, Stockheim - Sonneberg and Kronach - Nordhalben.
On July 15, 1950, the "Volksblatt" reported a workforce of 160 men; 13 steam locomotives and eight electric locomotives were stationed in Pressig at that time.
The electrification of the line in 1939 already minimized the need for locomotives and pusher locomotives.
From 1977 they were only used for freight trains.
Until 1991, at least 10,000 wagons were still being shunted per month.
Parts of the depot were demolished in 1982 and the rest in 1991.
Heidrich: "It is regrettable that a better use of the location, also in terms of freight traffic, has not been considered."
At Whitsun 1989, the Nuremberg railway division celebrated a pompous station festival in Pressig to mark the anniversary of "50 years of electrification Nuremberg - Saalfeld".
"There were 10,000 enthusiastic spectators here," recalls Georg Dinkel.
A little later the end.
On 1 June 1991, the last 30 men were withdrawn, the marshalling yard Pressig was history.
"The shunters and brake shoe layers did the most difficult work in train traffic," recalls Dinkel.
Any mistake would have had fatal consequences.
