The 125th anniversary of the District Association for Horticulture and Landscape Management was celebrated with a gala in the Dr.-Stammberger-Halle.
On 29 September 1893, the last founding impulses for the Kreisverband für Gartenbau und Landespflege Kulmbach were set with a fruit show in the Kulmbach clubhouse, and exactly 125 years later it celebrated a big anniversary on Saturday evening in the Kulmbach town hall.
Of course, it was still called differently at that time: It was founded by Mayor Wilhelm Flessa in 1893 as the "Bezirksobstbauverein Kulmbach Stadt und Land".
The purpose of the fruit growing association also differed from today's work - it was actually purely about fruit growing, nobody thought about flowers and horticulture at that time.
"At that time, in the era of the Enlightenment, the fruit tree was a favorite child of the elites," explained Günter Dippold in his speech.
Fruit trees were to line highways, so-called industrial gardens were created at schools.
Fruit growing is still the task of the 55 horticultural associations in the district of Kulmbach, which have almost 7000 members.
But this is far from exhausted the spectrum.
Near-natural horticulture, biological plant protection, village beautification and nutrition play just as important a role as the transfer of knowledge, a healthy diet and youth work.
The members of the Hutschdorf youth group "Moles" showed how versatile the tasks of a horticultural association are entertainingly on stage.
"Youth work is urgently needed, especially in the digital age," said district chairman Günter Reif, and Lord Mayor Henry Schramm also emphasized how important experiences in nature are for life.
Chestnut collecting was a huge thing for us children, I doubt that you can collect as much joy with smartphones & Co.
Schramm promised to plant two trees together with District Administrator Klaus Peter Söllner for the anniversary.
"The district association decides where they should stand," added District Administrator Söllner and emphasized the special importance of the horticultural associations for the villages.
The district association stands for ecology, beauty of the garden and green areas in the village.
