Farmers are allowed to start annual kink care on Monday
Schleswig-Holstein's farmers are allowed to start their annual kink care on Monday.
The "green walls", which are unique in Germany, have shaped the landscape of the sparsely forested federal state for around 200 years.
The up to five meter wide trees and scrubs are "forest substitutes" and for many animals and plants the last retreats.
Knicks connect as corridors scattered habitats, over which the exchange of organisms can still function, as the managing director of the Nature and Biodiversity Conservation Union Germany (NABU) in Schleswig-Holstein, Ingo Ludwichowski, said.
Knicks are living fences
The Knicks were created on the basis of an order of the Danish King Christian VI in 1766, who ruled over Schleswig-Holstein.
The "living fences" were not only field boundaries and cattle fences, they also provided the farmers with firewood and beams for their half-timbered houses.
Its name "Knick" also comes from that time: by "twisting" the branches, the dense, intertwined boundaries could develop.
Today, around 45,000 kilometres of hedges stretch between the North Sea and the Baltic Sea, giving the image of a woody, diversely structured landscape.
According to NABU, they are now used by around 7000 animal species as a replacement habitat.
Up to 1800 different species could live in one kilometre of bend and up to 30 pairs of birds could breed.
However, the kink can only fulfil its ecologically important function if it is cared for accordingly in winter.
Otherwise, it atrophies to a light row of trees, which loses not only biodiversity but also the windbreak effect, said Ludwichowski.
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, kink care may only be operated outside the breeding season from October to March.
